Question Text: Given the following URI https://courses.examsdigest.com/ccna, which part is the hostname?
Choices:
a. https
b. courses
c. courses.examsdigest.com
d. examsdigest.com
e. examsdigest.com/ccna
LLM Explanation: The hostname in the given URI is courses.examsdigest.com. The hostname is the part of the URI that identifies the host that is being accessed. It comes after the scheme (https://) and before the path (/ccna) if present.
URLs: ['IETF RFC 3986 - Uniform Resource Identifier (URI): Generic Syntax', 'Computer Networking: A Top-Down Approach, 7th Edition by Kurose and Ross']

Question Text: Which of the following protocols uses the port 443?
Choices:
a. HTTPS
b. HTTP
c. SMTP
d. SSH
LLM Explanation: HTTPS (Hypertext Transfer Protocol Secure) uses port 443 by default. It is the secure version of HTTP, which uses port 80. HTTPS encrypts the data transmitted between the client and server using SSL/TLS protocols, ensuring secure communication.
URLs: ['CCNA 200-301 Official Cert Guide, Wendell Odom, Cisco Press, 2020', 'https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/HTTPS']

Question Text: Which of the following protocols uses the port 80?
Choices:
a. HTTPS
b. HTTP
c. SMTP
d. SSH
LLM Explanation: HTTP (Hypertext Transfer Protocol) uses port 80 by default. It is the protocol used for transmitting web pages and other web content over the Internet. HTTPS uses port 443, SMTP uses port 25, and SSH uses port 22.
URLs: ['IANA Service Name and Transport Protocol Port Number Registry: https://www.iana.org/assignments/service-names-port-numbers/service-names-port-numbers.xhtml', 'Cisco Networking Academy: Introduction to Networks v7.0 (ITN) - Chapter 9: Transport Layer']

Question Text: Which of the following protocols uses the port 25?
Choices:
a. HTTPS
b. HTTP
c. SMTP
d. SSH
LLM Explanation: SMTP (Simple Mail Transfer Protocol) uses port 25 for sending email messages between servers. HTTPS uses port 443, HTTP uses port 80, and SSH uses port 22.
URLs: ['CCNA 200-301 Official Cert Guide, Volume 1 by Wendell Odom', 'RFC 821 - Simple Mail Transfer Protocol', 'https://www.iana.org/assignments/service-names-port-numbers/service-names-port-numbers.xhtml']

Question Text: Which of the following protocols uses the port 22?
Choices:
a. HTTPS
b. HTTP
c. SMTP
d. SSH
LLM Explanation: SSH (Secure Shell) uses port 22 by default. SSH is a secure protocol used for remote login and other secure network services over an unsecured network.
URLs: ['IANA Service Name and Transport Protocol Port Number Registry: https://www.iana.org/assignments/service-names-port-numbers/service-names-port-numbers.xhtml', 'SSH.com: SSH Port - Port 22: https://www.ssh.com/academy/ssh/port']

Question Text: Which of the following port numbers the SNMP protocol uses?
LLM Explanation: SNMP (Simple Network Management Protocol) uses UDP port 161 for sending and receiving requests between managers and agents. Port 161 is the standard port for SNMP and is widely used for network management and monitoring purposes.
URLs: ['IETF RFC 1157 - A Simple Network Management Protocol (SNMP)', 'Cisco Press CCNA 200-301 Official Cert Guide, Chapter 28: SNMP and Syslog']

Question Text: Which of the following port numbers the POP3 protocol uses?
LLM Explanation: POP3 (Post Office Protocol version 3) is an application-layer Internet standard protocol used by e-mail clients to retrieve e-mail from a server. POP3 uses TCP port 110 as its well-known port.
URLs: ['IETF RFC 1939: Post Office Protocol - Version 3 (https://tools.ietf.org/html/rfc1939)', 'IANA Service Name and Transport Protocol Port Number Registry (https://www.iana.org/assignments/service-names-port-numbers/service-names-port-numbers.xhtml)']

Question Text: Which of the following port numbers the DNS protocol uses?
LLM Explanation: The Domain Name System (DNS) protocol uses port 53 for its communication. DNS is used to translate domain names to IP addresses. When a DNS query is made by a client, it is sent to the DNS server using UDP or TCP on port 53.

Question Text: Which of the following options are things that a standard IP ACL could be configured to do? (Choose two answers.)
Choices:
a. Match the exact source IP address
b. Match all IP addresses in a subnet with one access-list command without matching other IP addresses
c. Match IP addresses 20.2.2.2 through 20.2.2.22 with one access-list command without matching other IP addresses
d. Match only the packetâ€™s destination IP address
LLM Explanation: A standard IP access control list (ACL) can be configured to match the exact source IP address of packets, as well as match only the packet's destination IP address. Standard ACLs do not have the capability to match a range or subnet of IP addresses with a single command.
URLs: ['CCNA 200-301 Official Cert Guide, Volume 1, Chapter 16: Access Control Lists (ACLs)', 'Cisco Documentation: Configure IP Access Control Lists (https://www.cisco.com/c/en/us/support/docs/security/ios-firewall/23602-confaccesslists.html)']

Question Text: One of the differences between named and numbered ACLs is that named ACLS using ACL subcommands, not global commands, to define the action and matching parameters.
Choices:
a. TRUE
b. FALSE
LLM Explanation: The statement is true. Named ACLs use ACL subcommands within the named ACL configuration mode to define the action (permit or deny) and matching parameters (source IP, destination IP, protocols, etc.). In contrast, numbered ACLs use global configuration commands to define the action and matching parameters directly under the global configuration mode.
URLs: ['Cisco CCNA 200-301 Official Cert Guide, Volume 1 by Wendell Odom, Chapter 25: Basic IPv4 Access Control Lists', 'Cisco Documentation: Configure IP Access Control Lists (https://www.cisco.com/c/en/us/support/docs/security/ios-firewall/23602-confaccesslists.html)']

Question Text: Given the following fields, which of those cannot be compared on an extended IP ACL?
Choices:
a. Application protocol
b. Destination IP address
c. Source IP address
d. URL
e. TOS Byte
LLM Explanation: Extended IP ACLs cannot compare URLs or the TOS (Type of Service) byte. Extended ACLs can filter based on source and destination IP addresses, protocol type (e.g., TCP, UDP, ICMP), source and destination ports (for TCP/UDP), and some protocol-specific flags and options. However, they do not have visibility into the application layer to filter based on URLs. The TOS byte is also not a filterable field in standard extended ACLs.
URLs: ['Cisco CCNA 200-301 Official Cert Guide, Volume 2, Chapter 16: Access Control Lists (ACLs)', 'https://www.cisco.com/c/en/us/support/docs/security/ios-firewall/23602-confaccesslists.html']

Question Text:
Your task is to type a one-line standard ACL that matches the following criteria. All access-list commands use the number 1 in the command.
Criteria #1: Permit packets from 186.33.2.3
ACL command #1: ______________________
Choices:
a. access-list 1 permit 186.33.2.3
b. access-list 1 deny 186.33.2.3
c. access-list 1 permit 186.33.2.0
d. access-list 1 deny 186.33.0.0
LLM Explanation: The correct answer is 'a. access-list 1 permit 186.33.2.3'. This command creates a standard ACL with the number 1 that specifically permits packets from the IP address 186.33.2.3. The other options are incorrect because they either use the 'deny' keyword instead of 'permit' or specify a different IP address or network that does not match the given criteria.
URLs: ['Cisco CCNA 200-301 Official Cert Guide, Volume 1 by Wendell Odom (Chapter 16: Access Control Lists)', 'https://www.cisco.com/c/en/us/td/docs/ios-xml/ios/sec_data_acl/configuration/15-mt/sec-data-acl-15-mt-book/sec-create-ip-apply-acl.html']

Question Text:
Your task is to type a one-line standard ACL that matches the following criteria. All access-list commands use the number 1 in the command.
Criteria #2: Permit packets from hosts with 56.57.2 as the first three octets
ACL command #2: ______________________
Choices:
a. access-list 1 permit 56.57.2.0 0.0.0.255
b. access-list 1 permit 57.57.2.0 0.0.0.255
c. access-list 1 permit 56.57.2.0 0.0.255.255
d. access-list 1 deny 56.57.2.0 0.0.0.255
LLM Explanation: The correct answer is 'a'. The ACL command 'access-list 1 permit 56.57.2.0 0.0.0.255' matches the criteria to permit packets from hosts with 56.57.2 as the first three octets. The wildcard mask 0.0.0.255 allows any value in the last octet, effectively permitting all hosts in the 56.57.2.0/24 subnet.
URLs: ['Cisco CCNA Official Cert Guide, Wendell Odom, Chapter 12: Security', 'https://www.cisco.com/c/en/us/support/docs/security/ios-firewall/23602-confaccesslists.html']

Question Text:
Your task is to type a one-line standard ACL that matches the following criteria. All access-list commands use the number 1 in the command.
Criteria #3: Permit packets from hosts with 56.57 as the first two octets
ACL command #3: ______________________
Choices:
a. access-list 1 permit 56.57.0.0 0.255.255.255
b. access-list 1 permit 56.57.0.0 0.0.255.255
c. access-list 1 permit 56.58.0.0 0.0.255.255
d. access-list 1 permit 56.57.0.0 0.0.0.0
LLM Explanation: To permit packets from hosts with 56.57 as the first two octets, the correct wildcard mask should be 0.0.255.255. This mask allows any value in the last two octets while fixing the first two octets as 56.57. Option 'a' uses 0.255.255.255 which is not a valid wildcard mask. Option 'c' has an incorrect wildcard mask and also permits 56.58 in the first two octets. Option 'd' uses 0.0.0.0 which would only permit the exact IP 56.57.0.0.
URLs: ['CCNA 200-301 Official Cert Guide, Wendell Odom, Chapter 16: Configuring Standard IPv4 ACLs', 'https://www.cisco.com/c/en/us/support/docs/security/ios-firewall/23602-confaccesslists.html']

Question Text:
Your task is to type a one-line extended ACL that matches the following criteria. All access-list commands use the number 101 in the command.
Criteria #4: Permit packets from web client 65.5.5.5, sent to a web server in subnet 65.5.6.0/24
ACL command #4: ______________________
Choices:
a. access-list 101 permit tcp host 65.5.5.5 65.5.6.0 0.0.0.255 eq 23
b. access-list 101 permit any any
c. access-list 101 permit tcp host 65.5.5.5 65.5.6.0 0.0.0.255 eq www
d. access-list 101 deny tcp host 65.5.5.5 65.5.6.0 0.0.0.255 eq www
LLM Explanation: The correct answer is c. The access-list command should permit TCP traffic from the specific host 65.5.5.5 to the subnet 65.5.6.0/24 on the www (HTTP) port 80. Option a uses the wrong port (telnet port 23 instead of www). Option b permits any traffic, which is too broad. Option d denies the traffic instead of permitting it.
URLs: ['Cisco CCNA Official Cert Guide, Chapter 16: Access Control Lists', 'https://www.cisco.com/c/en/us/td/docs/switches/lan/catalyst2960/software/release/12-2_55_se/configuration/guide/scg_2960/swacl.html']

Question Text:
Your task is to type a one-line extended ACL that matches the following criteria. All access-list commands use the number 101 in the command.
Criteria #5: Permit any and every IPv4 packet
ACL command #5: ______________________
Choices:
a. access-list 101 permit ip any any
b. access-list 101 deny ip any any
c. access-list 101 permit ip 0.0.0.0 any
d. access-list 101 permit ip any 0.0.0.0
LLM Explanation: The correct answer is 'a' (access-list 101 permit ip any any). This extended ACL command permits any and every IPv4 packet because it uses the 'any' keyword for both the source and destination IP addresses. The 'any' keyword matches all possible IPv4 addresses, effectively allowing all IPv4 traffic.
URLs: ['Cisco CCNA Official Cert Guide, Wendell Odom, Chapter 12: ACLs and Firewalls', 'Cisco Documentation: Configure IP Access Control Lists, https://www.cisco.com/c/en/us/support/docs/security/ios-firewall/23602-confaccesslists.html']

Question Text: Which of the following commands display the configuration of an IPv4 ACL, including line numbers? (Choose two answers.)
Choices:
a. show running-config
b. show startup-config
c. show ip access-lists
d. show access-lists
LLM Explanation: The 'show ip access-lists' and 'show access-lists' commands both display the configuration of IPv4 ACLs, including the line numbers. The 'show running-config' and 'show startup-config' commands display the entire device configuration, which includes ACLs but does not provide a focused view with line numbers.

Question Text: Type the access-list command that permits all packets sent from hosts in subnet 14.15.16.0/24. Use the ACL number 50 for the ACL rule.
Choices:
a. access-list 50 permit 14.15.17.0 0.0.0.255
b. access-list 50 deny 14.15.16.0 0.0.0.255
c. access-list 50 permit 14.15.16.0 0.255.255.255
d. access-list 50 permit 14.15.16.0 0.0.0.255
LLM Explanation: The correct access-list command to permit all packets sent from hosts in subnet 14.15.16.0/24 using ACL number 50 is 'access-list 50 permit 14.15.16.0 0.0.0.255'. The command syntax is 'access-list [ACL number] [permit/deny] [source IP] [wildcard mask]'. The wildcard mask 0.0.0.255 matches the inverse of the subnet mask 255.255.255.0, allowing all hosts within the 14.15.16.0/24 subnet.
URLs: ['Cisco CCNA Official Cert Guide, Chapter 12: Access Control Lists', 'https://www.cisco.com/c/en/us/support/docs/security/ios-firewall/23602-confaccesslists.html']

Question Text: Given the following access-list command access-list 2 permit 192.168.4.0 0.0.0.255, choose the exact range of IP addresses, matched by the command.
LLM Explanation: The access-list command 'access-list 2 permit 192.168.4.0 0.0.0.255' matches the IP address range 192.168.4.0 - 192.168.4.255. The first part '192.168.4.0' specifies the network address, and the second part '0.0.0.255' is the wildcard mask. A wildcard mask of '0.0.0.255' means that the last octet can be any value from 0 to 255, while the first three octets must match exactly. Therefore, the range covers all IP addresses starting with '192.168.4'.
URLs: ['Cisco CCNA Official Cert Guide, Chapter 6: Access Control Lists', 'https://www.cisco.com/c/en/us/support/docs/security/ios-firewall/23602-confaccesslists.html']

Question Text: The range of valid ACL numbers for standard numbered IP ACLs is:
LLM Explanation: The valid range for standard numbered IP ACLs is 1-99 and 1300-1999. The extended range of 1300-1999 was introduced to allow more standard ACLs to be created. Choice 'b' incorrectly specifies the extended range as 1700-1999. Choices 'c' and 'd' have incorrect ranges for the standard ACL numbers.
URLs: ['Cisco CCNA 200-301 Official Cert Guide, Volume 1, Chapter 16: Access Control Lists (ACLs)', 'https://www.cisco.com/c/en/us/support/docs/security/ios-firewall/23602-confaccesslists.html']

Question Text:
The ACL 55 on R1 has four statements, in the following order, with address and wildcard mask values as follows:
1. 20.0.0.0 0.255.255.255
2. 20.20.0.0 0.0.255.255
3. 20.20.20.0 0.0.0.255
4. 2.2.2.0 0.0.0.255
If a router tried to match a packet sourced from IP address 20.20.20.20 using this ACL, which ACL statement does a router consider the packet to have matched?
Choices:
a. First statement
b. Second statement
c. Third statement
d. Forth statement
e. Implied deny at the end of the ACL
LLM Explanation: The router will match the packet to the third statement in the ACL. When a router processes an ACL, it goes through the statements in sequential order from top to bottom. The packet with source IP 20.20.20.20 matches the third statement because it falls within the range specified by 20.20.20.0 0.0.0.255. Even though it also matches the less specific ranges in the first and second statements, the router stops processing the ACL as soon as it finds a match, which in this case is the third statement.
URLs: ['Cisco CCNA 200-301 Official Cert Guide, Volume 1, Chapter 16: Access Control Lists (ACLs)', 'https://www.cisco.com/c/en/us/support/docs/security/ios-firewall/23602-confaccesslists.html']

Question Text: Which of the following access-list denies packets with a UDP header, any source IP address with source port greater than 10455, a destination IP address 30.3.3.3 and a destination port equal to 25?
Choices:
a. access-list 101 deny udp any gt 10455 host 30.3.3.3 eq 28
b. access-list 101 deny udp any gt 10455 host 30.3.3.3 eq 25
c. access-list 101 deny tcp any gt 10455 host 30.3.3.3 eq 25
d. access-list 101 deny udp any gt 25 host 30.3.3.3 eq 25
LLM Explanation: The correct access-list command to deny UDP packets with any source IP address, source port greater than 10455, destination IP 30.3.3.3, and destination port 25 is: 'access-list 101 deny udp any gt 10455 host 30.3.3.3 eq 25'. This matches the syntax and parameters specified in the question.
URLs: ['Cisco CCNA Official Cert Guide, Chapter 12: Access Control Lists', 'https://www.cisco.com/c/en/us/td/docs/ios-xml/ios/sec_data_acl/configuration/15-mt/sec-data-acl-15-mt-book/sec-create-ip-apply.html']

Question Text: Which of the following access-list denies packets with a UDP header, a source IP address 30.3.3.3 and a source port greater than 10455, any destination IP address 30.3.3.3 with destination port equal to 25?
Choices:
a. access-list 101 deny udp host 30.3.3.3 gt 10455 any eq 30
b. access-list 101 deny udp host 30.3.3.3 gt 25 any eq 25
c. access-list 101 deny udp host 30.0.0.0 gt 10455 any eq 25
d. access-list 101 deny udp host 30.3.3.3 gt 10455 any eq 25
LLM Explanation: The correct access list to deny the specified UDP packets is 'd': access-list 101 deny udp host 30.3.3.3 gt 10455 any eq 25. This ACL matches UDP packets from the specific source IP 30.3.3.3 with source ports greater than 10455, destined to any IP address with destination port 25. The other options have incorrect syntax or parameters that do not match the question criteria.
URLs: ['Cisco CCNA Official Cert Guide, Chapter 12: Security Fundamentals', 'https://www.cisco.com/c/en/us/td/docs/ios-xml/ios/sec_data_acl/configuration/xe-16-10/sec-data-acl-xe-16-10-book/sec-create-ip-al.html']

Question Text: Choose the wildcard mask that matches all IP packets in the subnet 46.45.44.0, and mask 255.255.255.0.
LLM Explanation: The wildcard mask is the inverse of the subnet mask. To calculate the wildcard mask, subtract each octet of the subnet mask from 255. In this case, the subnet mask is 255.255.255.0, so the wildcard mask would be 0.0.0.255 (255 - 255 = 0, 255 - 255 = 0, 255 - 255 = 0, 255 - 0 = 255).
URLs: ['CCNA 200-301 Official Cert Guide, Volume 1 by Wendell Odom, Chapter 12: Perspectives on IPv4 Subnetting', 'https://www.cisco.com/c/en/us/support/docs/ip/access-lists/26448-ACLsamples.html']
